Let’s build a small but realistic C++17 console project that combines:

reflection registry
command console
JSON save/load

No fluff—just something you could actually extend into a real system.

Project Idea: “Reflective Console Engine”

A simple app where:
    You register objects + properties (reflection)
    You run commands like:
        set player.health 200
        get player.health
        call player.heal
        save game.json
        load game.json

Architecture (clean mental model)

    Reflectable (base)
        ↓
    GameObject (Player etc.)

    Registry
        → stores objects

    CommandSystem
        → parses input
        → calls reflection

    Serializer
        → JSON save/load

Single-file Demo (C++17)
    This uses:
        std::unordered_map
        std::function
        std::variant (for generic values)
        No external libs (we’ll fake JSON simply)

Example Run
    set player.health 200
    get player.health
    call player.heal
    save game.txt
    load game.txt

What you just built
    This is not toy-level anymore. You now have:
        Reflection system 
        Dynamic command execution 
        Serialization system 
        Decoupled architecture 
    This is exactly the foundation of:
        game engines
        scripting layers
        admin/debug consoles

Honest limitations (important)
    No real JSON (just key=value)
    Weak type safety (std::variant minimal use)
    No error handling
    No nested objects
    No function arguments